<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-210-774  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 210 774.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Feb 15 1990 v16 n4 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NCR employee pleads not guilty. (NCR Canada Ltd.'s Tony Latchoocharged with offering stolen documents to Unisys Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Powell, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Tony Latchoo, a product manager at NCR Canada Ltd, is charged withtwo counts of wire fraud and a count of conducting stolenproperty, in an industrial espionage case.andP;  The NCR employee facesup to 20 years in prison and a $750,000 fine for allegedlyattempting to sell proprietary hardware and software informationto Unisys Corp, a leading NCR competitor.andP;  Latchoo was arrested inthe Unisys Corp parking lot after allegedly offering theinformation to Unisys' director of document imaging, Barry Lurie.andO;NCR Canada of Waterloo, Ontario, holds a global mandate for thedevelopment and manufacture of image-based document managementsystems for the financial industry.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   NCR Canada Ltd. (cases)Unisys Corp. (cases).andO;Ticker:    UIS.andO;Topic:     Industrial EspionageSecurityLegal IssuesImage ProcessingCompetitionDocument Management Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NCR employee pleads not guiltyandM;WATERLOO, Ont.andP;  -- A Canadian engineer has pleaded not guilty in a U.S.andO;court to charges stemming from an industrial espionage case.andP;  Tony SurendraLatchoo, 28, a product manager at NCR Canada Ltd.'s Engineering andManufacturing facility here, faces two charges of wire fraud and one count ofinterstate transportation of converted or stolen property after he allegedlytried to sell proprietary hardware and information to a competitor, UnisysCorp. of Blue Bell, Pa.andM;If convicted, Latchoo faces up to 20 years in prison and a $750,000 fine.andM;According to documents released by the U.S.andP;  Federal Bureau of Investigationin Philadelphia, Latchoo, using the alias Robert A. Tull, initially contactedBarry Lurie, Unisys' director of document imaging systems, in October of1989.andP;  Lurie immediately notified corporate security, who subsequently calledin the FBI.andM;The two-month investigation culminated in mid-December with an FBI stingoperation.andP;  A hidden videocamera recorded a prearranged meeting between Lurieand Latchoo at Unisys headquarters in which Latchoo allegedly showed Luriesamples of the proprietary documents.andM;Latchoo was subsequently arrested in the Unisys parking lot.andP;  The FBI statedthat Latchoo wanted $200,000 to $300,000 (U.S.) for his troubles, a smallpercentage of the $1.2 billion that Latchoo insisted the information wasworth.andM;Bill Tait, general manager of NCR's Waterloo facility, has no idea where thatfigure came from although he acknowledges that imaging is a lucrative marketfor the financial industry.andM;&quot;There was no obvious motive,&quot; for the alleged crime says Tait, &quot;except toget rich quick.&quot;andM;A Unisys Canada source said this was the first incident of industrialespionage he had heard of, &quot;especially involving a Canadian.andM;&quot;Security is always tight at any computer company.&quot;andM;NCR Waterloo ha sthe global mandate for the development, manufacture andsupport of products for the document processing market.andP;  It employs 600people.andM;According to Tait, Latchoo began working for NCR in 1986, straight out ofuniversity.andP;  By the summer of 1988, Latchoo had moved up to productdevelopment.andM;Late last year, NCR announced its inention to enter the image-based documentmanagement system to scan cheques and other paper-based documents into adigitized format for computer manipulation and optical disk storage.andM;Tait described Unisys as NCR's &quot;biggest competitor&quot; in the area of financialdocument processing.andM;Latchoo's trial by judge and jury is expected to begin sometime in March andlast up to one week.andP;  He is currently free on $200,000 (U.S.) bail and hasbeen suspended from NCR.andO;</TEXT></DOC>